{"$ambrosia":"aero:interactive:9417ac60-5f60-11ea-8e69-affb2224d7e8:*","$id":"086ce230-44e0-11ed-80e3-0e0cc1557ba9","$workspaceId":"7fff47c0-44d6-11ed-bcef-d5307f42495c","$projectId":"86cb0040-44df-11ed-8442-dbcbc27803ca","annotations":[],"configSchemaVersion":"/pluginGenericSchema/v1","config":{"stage":{"sections":[{"rowsAreFullWidth":false,"backgroundImageUrl":"","rows":[{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"heading-one","ref":"5220a299-749a-4a58-9206-d8d9b9e2b7ce","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"16.2 Capital Structure in Perfect Capital Markets","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"f2b3cb8d-919a-4726-ae9d-916681abee9e"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"943723a9-28ea-4d40-b76b-65ab54990fbe","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"When a firm issues debt, equity, or other securities to fund a new investment, there are many potential consequences of its decision. By far the most important question for a financial manager is whether different choices will affect the value of the firm and thus the amount of capital it can raise. We begin by considering this question in a simple environment—a perfect capital market. A ","marks":[]},{"data":{"ref":"31bfd2fa-9ed1-45c3-982a-c042ffb1d35a","stage":{"ref":"c5237445-65c1-4934-b55c-2525060a7056","sections":[{"ref":"cd49855f-d0ed-4c88-979e-7266806a6720","rows":[{"ref":"929ea2af-e394-4fa6-863d-180015bdbdc4","columns":[{"ref":"a0ccd072-51fd-4ea7-8478-b8aabf66e895","stageElements":[{"ref":"98da7774-1781-4e6a-bbf7-66e91b350312","type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"button","ref":"e2b725f7-4877-4c1d-9397-5bd4537ee88b","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"d48ff5cd-9fdb-4601-b523-d19e66773615","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"A set of conditions in which investors and firms can trade the same set of securities at competitive market prices; there are no frictions and the firm’s financing decisions do not change the cash flows generated by its investments.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}],"data":{}}]}}}]}]}]}]}},"nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"perfect capital market","marks":[{"type":"bold"}]}],"object":"inline","type":"key-term","ref":"a51630e3-d4d7-4f08-98b2-ec172483c04f"},{"object":"text","text":" is a market in which:","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"118daf05-5a37-4a1b-9d94-b0ce32ba26f2"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"ordered-list","data":{"listOptionType":"1","startValue":1},"ref":"5e262345-85ca-48eb-8618-4eeb21fe1dd2","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"4d0fd7fd-e7de-4ac6-927a-f8b0194a2064","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"24144072-c9e7-4863-866e-9344dd5f4ede","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Securities are fairly priced. ","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" Investors and firms can trade the same set of securities at competitive market prices equal to the present value of their future cash flows.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"99fc5448-2736-48f2-92ce-6cea5c9fd6ef","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"33a3debf-224b-4771-a4d9-29d14a60ecdc","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"There are no tax consequences or transactions costs. ","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" There are no tax consequences, transactions costs, or other issuance costs associated with financing decisions or security trading.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]},{"object":"block","type":"list-item","data":{"direction":"auto"},"ref":"976d7c63-db0a-4690-bac3-10745bc0cf12","nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"957be990-8bb0-4054-88fa-c7983d1b9bd3","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"Investment cash flows are independent of financing choices. ","marks":[{"type":"italic"}]},{"object":"text","text":" A firm’s financing decisions do not change the cash flows generated by its investments, nor do they reveal new information about those cash flows.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}]}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"06370471-182f-4f1d-bcb0-322d79a47fb6"}]}]},{"columns":[{"stageElements":[{"type":"stage-element-text","value":{"object":"value","document":{"object":"document","data":{},"nodes":[{"object":"block","type":"paragraph","ref":"7dc5cc0a-4c9c-45e3-814a-d77f62e30662","nodes":[{"object":"text","text":"The assumption of perfect capital markets may seem narrow and unrealistic. We will see, however, that by starting with them we will gain important insight into the true benefits and costs of leverage.","marks":[]}],"data":{}}]}},"config":{"cssClass":""},"ref":"f4625513-6613-45d0-859c-832f29f9667c"}]}]}]}]},"screenType":"","transitions":{"enter":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""},"exit":{"animation":"","duration":0,"easing":"","customKeyframes":""}},"lockElements":false,"learnerCurrentAttempt":1,"footer":{"buttonText":"Next","buttonIcon":"Arrow","showFooter":false,"showHistoryNavButtons":false,"previewFooter":false,"position":"Fixed to screen bottom","footerComponent":{"showFooterDropArea":"hide","width":100,"footerComponentsAlignment":"right"}},"styles":{"background":{},"stage":{"maxWidth":940,"background":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","responsive":true,"padding":{"vertical":60,"horizontal":60},"border":{"color":"rgba(224, 224, 224, 1)","radius":0,"width":0}},"elements":{"padding":{"vertical":10,"horizontal":10}},"footer":{"buttonColor":"rgba(0, 115, 202, 1)","textColor":"rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.7)","backgroundColor":"rgba(255, 255, 255, 1)","paddin